 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid7235776 (Sidgwick 1964: 198)}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 . Sidgwick also put this contrast in terms of 舠'd2 Universal舡'd3 and 舠'd2Egoistic Reason.舡'd3 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 T}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 his resonates with Sidgwickquote s own famous 舠'd2dualism of practical reason, 舡'd3 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 but }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 it fails to capture an essential feature that }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 he}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 stresses elsewhere, namely, that 舠'd2conscience舡'd3 in modern ethical thought is essentially conceived in relation to 舠'd2quasi-jural notions舡'd3 of obligation, 舠'd2duty,舡'd3  and right (Sidgwick 1967: 105).}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid5141373 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1  \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0  23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid5141373 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid5141373   Ethical }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041 principles}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid5141373 , however universal or impersonal, need not take a juridical form.}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 We might, therefore, put Sidgwickquote  s point this way: Whereas ancient ethics recognized a single fundamental ethical concept and source of normative reasons, the good, modern ethics came to recognize two, the right as well as the good.  \par Sidgwickquote s central thought, I would say his central insight, is that, for the Greeks, 舠'd2}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid9375360 Virtue or Right action}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   [for example, Aristotlequote s idea of }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 an }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 action}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 quote s}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 being noble and choiceworthy in itself (1980: II.3-4)] is}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid9375360 commonly regarded as only a species of the Good}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 舡'd3  (Sidgwick 1967: 105). In modern thought, by contrast, we find a distinctive ethical conception, that of morality\emdash including moral obligation and rights\emdash which }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid9851930 purports}{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 to provide reasons for action that are very different from and that can trump considerations of the good, whether the agentquote s own good, or even good impersonally conceived.}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0   23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809   In other words, there is a conceptual difference, for the moderns, between the thought that an action will advance either the agentquote s good or overall good, on the one hand, and the thought that, perhaps because o f that, the action is morally obligatory, a duty, or wrong not to do, on the other.}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  \par This is the idea Butler gives voice to when he says that 舠'd2authority,舡'd3 indeed 舠'd2supreme authority,舡'd3 is part of the very idea of 舠'd2conscience舡'd3 (e.g., 1983, 3.\u182'a62),}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0   23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 Also: \uc1舠'd2 you cannot form a notion of this faculty, conscience, without taking in judgment, direction, superintendency. This is a constituent part of the idea, that is, of the faculty itself舡'd3 (1983: 2.\u182'a614). }}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 and what Kant expresses in his doctrine of the moral law as a categorical imperative. Let us call this the }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 authority of right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373  , that is,}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 the thesis that considerations of moral right, wrong, duty, and  obligation have an independent normative force that neither reduces to nor can be derived solely from that of the good (though it may partly depend upon it). It is consistent with the authority of right, so formulated, that we might have but the single m oral duty of promoting the good, or even of promoting our own good. The authority of right would still claim that any such duty could not follow directly from any facts about the good taken by themselves.  \par By speaking of the }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 authority}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 of the right I mean to echo Sidgwickquote s thought that the modern conception of right is a 舠'd2quasi-jural notion, 舡'd3 that is, that it is conceptually tied to the idea of legitimate or }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid2955583 de jure}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \i 34\insrsid354734 authority}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 .}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar \s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0  23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \cs17 34\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid3673592 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid2430041\charrsid3673592 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041  Of course, Anscombe used this element to criticize modern moral philosophy as requiring theological voluntarist foundations it no longer accepted (Anscombe 1958).}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid5141373 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 I shall interpret Sidgwickquote s }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 to entail }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  that the authority of right, so understood, is a distinctively modern thesis. In this paper, I wish to discuss Hobbesquote s moral philosophy in relation to }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 authority of right}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 . The dominant scholarly opinion, including my own until recently, has been that Hobbes denies }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 this thesis}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   since he holds that all obligations and duties derive their normative force from their relation to the good, in particular, to the agentquote s own good, or even more specifically, the agentquote s self-preservation. Now, however, I am not so sure.  \par In }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 The Second-Person Standpoint}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , I argue that the concepts of}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 moral right, wrong, and rights, which }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 we inherit from modern ethics}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 ,}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 are irreducibly }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734  second personal}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 . They operate within a conceptual network that essentially includes the idea of a distinctive kind of reason for acting, what I call a }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734  second-personal reason}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  , that is conceptually related to legitimate claims or demands that someone has the authority to address to the agent (or that the agent has, at least under a certain guise, the authority to address to herself). It is the  element of address that brings in the grammatical second person. Claims and demands necessarily have }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid5141373 addressees}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  , whether individuals, groups, or the public at large.  \par In this way, I argue, the ideas of moral obligation, right, wrong, and rights, are conceptually tied to that of }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid14287623 responsibility}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid15145894 to}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 someone in the sense of }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid14287623 accountability}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 or answerability. Moral obligations are what we are answerable for doing. But answerable to whom? Who has the authority to hold us accountable? According to early modern  theological voluntarists like Pufendorf and Locke, we are accountable to God, who has authority over all his creatures. More defensibly, I argue, we are accountable to one another (and indeed to ourselves) as representative persons or members of the mora l  community. What we are morally obligated to do is what we have the authority, as representative persons, to demand of each other and ourselves that we do. I argue that the seeds of this more adequate view can be found in the voluntarists themselves, li ke Pufendorf, who holds that to see oneself as subject to obligation, one must be able to }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid4017659 hold oneself}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   responsible through blame. This presupposes, I argue, not just anyonequote s }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid2521289 individual authority}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , not even Godquote s, but }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 both Godquote s}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 and our }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid2521289 representative authority}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 , as representative persons. To hold oneself responsible and blame oneself, one must be able to see oneself as being }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 to blame}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  , that is, blame}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid15145894 worth}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 y; and this judgment must be able to be made not from any individualquote s perspective, not even Godquote  s, but from an essentially shareable standpoint available to any moral agent. \par Moral rights, on the other hand, are conceptually tied }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 to }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid5141373 individual authority }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid5141373 rather than }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid5141373 representative}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid5141373 authority}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 . A claim right, for example, entails a right holderquote s individual auth ority to insist on certain conduct, to waive her right, to consent to what would otherwise be a violation, to hold others accountable for violations (or to choose not to at her discretion), and so on. It follows that so-called 舠'd2directed舡 'd3 or 舠'd2bipolar舡'd3 obligations }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 to}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   others that are the conceptual correlates of claim rights also implicate this individual authority. If you have a right against me that I not step on your feet, then I am obligated }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 to you}{tlch cs1  \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 not to do so, and you consequently have the authority to demand this of me and hold me accountable for it.}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar \s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0  23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid2442748 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid2442748 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041 In a just society, not by taking the law into onequote s ow n hands, but through civil procedures.}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 Of course, if I have a moral obligation }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid3673592 to you}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 not to do this, we can (and typically do) also think, that I have a moral obligation }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid12558 period}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   not to do so as well. It is a reflection of this that in cases  that are sufficiently serious to warrant a criminal law, we think that the question of whether to prosecute and how to hold someone accountable for violations is not distinctively up to the victim, but is properly decided by the people and their represent atives.  \par As I said, my aim is to discuss Hobbesquote s moral philosophy in relation to }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid3673592 the authority of right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid10027162 .}{tlch cs1  \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 Hobbes is, by anyonequote s accounting, a modern moral philosopher. Partly what we have in mind in so categorizing him, of course, is Hobbesquote s respect fo r the emerging empirical sciences, his metaphysical naturalism or materialism, or perhaps his search for something like Cartesian foundations and certainty. But it is also widely agreed that Hobbes can be placed within a modern natural law tradition that  is attempting to theorize the }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid16468054 concept}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 of morality }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid16468054 along something like the lines}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 I have just been sketching.  \par At the same time, however, the preponderant view among Hobbes scholars is that Hobbes does not accept, nor is there anything in his philosophy that should lead him to accept, the }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid16468054  authority of right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 as we have defined it. Even when interpreters are agreed that Hobbes distinguishes moral obligation and the requirements of the law of nature from considerations of the (agentquote  s own) good, as for example in Hobbesquote s reply to the fool in }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 Leviathan }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : 15.\u167'a44-5), the predominant view has been that Hobbes nonetheless }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid4263871 derives}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   the normative force of laws of nature from that of the agentquote s own good, the good of self-preservation or peace, or something similar.}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar \s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0  23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 See, e.g., Darwall 1995}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041 , 1997,}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 and 2000, Gauthier 1979, Irwin 2008: 159-178, and Kavka 1986 and 1995.}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 So understood, the right has no fundamental independent authority.  \par On what seems to be the most common interpretation, Hobbesquote s view is some kind of 舠'd2rule-舡'd3 or 舠'd2indirect egoism舡'd3 (Gauthier 1979, Kavka 1985, 1995, Irwin 2008). Although considerations of  moral right do not themselves }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid4263871 reduce}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 to those of the agentquote s own good, the rightquote s normative force nonetheless }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid4263871 derives}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   from these. According to Hobbes, it is only because anyone will do better, because he will be likelier to survive and enjoy the benefit s of peace, if his deliberative practical reasoning is not egoistic but gives independent and even overriding weight to considerations of moral right (when these properly bind, e.g., with the sovereignquote  s backing), that these latter considerations have any normative force at all. Nonetheless, because these benefits can arise only when they are pursued }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid2429256 indirectly}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , by }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid16468054 directly}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  following the laws of nature, considerations of right do have a normative force that is distinct from that of the good, however derivative it may be. Indeed, if it is beneficial for agents to give the right supreme normative authority, that is, as }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid16468054 overriding}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   the good, then, according to an indirect egoist (or more, generally, indirect consequentialist) interpretation, considerations of the right will then really have this normative authority, albeit derivatively. \par I used myself to accept some version of this interpretation (Darwall 1995, 1997, and 2000). Although Hobbes employs a concept of }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid9635778 obligation}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 that he explicitly defines independently of the good in terms of the right (roughly, the state one comes to be in when one 舠'd2lays down舡'd3 or 舠'd2transfers舡'd3 a right (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : 14.\u167'a47)), it nonetheless seemed to me that any }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid6100928 normative force}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   this defined notion could have within Hobbesquote s moral philosophy woul d have to be inherited from that of the good, along something like the indirect egoist or consequentialist lines I just sketched. More recently, however, I have come to believe that this is not right. In what follows, I want to lay out aspects of Hobbes quote s views that lead in the direction of }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid9580712 the}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid9580712 authority of right}{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , that is, fairly central elements of his thought that require that obligation and right not simply not reduce to, but also that they not solely derive their normative force }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid6100928 entirely }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 from, that of the good. I shall argue, moreover, that these elements require the authority of right precisely because they are }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid2039970 second personal}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 in the way I mentioned above\emdash they concern a fundamental form of accountability to one another. \par I do not claim, I should make  clear, that Hobbes himself accepted the authority of right, or even that he would have on reflection. I am claiming, rather, that there are important aspects of his thought that lead in this direction. And I shall also claim that at least some elements  that seem decisively to lead }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 away}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 from the authority of right, in fact do not. In this, I shall be agreeing with much of Sharon Lloydquote  s recent interpretation of the laws of nature as articulating a conception of }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 reciprocity}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , or, as I shall argue, mutual ac countability, that cannot, by its very nature, be derived from the good (Lloyd 2009).}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar \s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0  23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid16278097 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid16278097 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041  Lloyd follows Rawls (e.g., Rawls 2006) in interpreting the laws of nature in terms of the }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid16278097 reasonable}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041 . Unlike R awls, she does not see Hobbes as trying (impossibly) to derive the reasonable from the rational.}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid12455619  \par }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 I will proceed as follows. Before turning to Hobbes, I shall begin, in Section I, by exhibiting how second-personal elements of the modern conception of morality are pr esent right from the start in what is frequently regarded as modern moral theoryquote s originating work: Grotiusquote s }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 Rights of War and Peace}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  . Then, in Section II, I shall present what I take to be the best case for attributing to Hobbes a rejection of the authority of right and the view that practical normative force must ultimately derive from the agentquote  s own ends (via instrumental practical reason), or the agentquote s own good, or the good period (whether personal or impersonal). In Section III, I shall discuss a basic obstacle that is faced by any attempt to derive the rightquote  s normative force from that of the good, namely, that no such account can explain the rightquote s second-personal character. Then in Section IV, I shall exhibit how Hobbesquote s own }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid10881568  claims about the}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   right presuppose this second-personal element and how aspects of his view that may seem decisively to be odds with it are not in fact. Finally, in Section V, I explain how Hobbes might accept the authority of right, and so more adequately capture its se cond-personal character, consistently with his deepest philosophical commitments.  \par To anticipate, the main idea will be as follows. Strawson pointed out in 舠'd2Freedom and Resentment舡'd3 that any attempt to derive attributions of blameworthiness (and so implici tly, moral obligation and right) from considerations of the good, for example, from the good consequences of holding someone responsible and blaming him, will give a reason of the wrong kind to support the attribution (Strawson 1968).}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0   23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 \uc1舠'd2 [E]fficacy . . . in regulating behaviour in socially desirable ways舡'd3 is not, Strawson says, a reason 舠'd2of the right sort舡'd3 for practices of moral responsibility 舠'd2as we understand them舡'd3 (1968: 72,74).}}}{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 The reason why this is so is that the good is as a conceptual matter normative for }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 desire}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  , whereas obligation, }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4544013 right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , and blameworthiness, are normative for the attitudes through which we hold people responsible and }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 blame}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 them\emdash what Strawson dubbed 舠'd2}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid10881568 reactive attitudes}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 ,舡'd3 like resentment, indignation, and guilt. It is a conceptual truth that if something is morally wrong, then it is an action of a kind that would be }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid9051447 blameworthy}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , were it done without adequate excuse.  \par Now on the orthodox view, Hobbes is a value subjectivist; he holds that claims about the good are reducible to claims about desire satisfaction. I have argued, however, that this is not right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734\charrsid8284233 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 (Darwall 2000). When Hobbes says that 舠'd2}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid3085518  whatsoever is the object of any man's appetite or desire, that is it which he for his part calleth good}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 舡'd3 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 : 6.\u167'a47), Hobbes is saying not that when we call something good we assert that we desire it. He is saying that when we desire something, we call it good. The right way to read Hobbesquote  s metaethics of the good, therefore, is as expressivism or projectivism rather than subjectivism. This is also supported by Hobbesquote  s acceptance of a Galilean projectivist view of color, which he explicitly analogizes to value (Darwall 2000). I shall argue by analogy that the most philosophically satisf actory way for Hobbes to develop aspects of his view that tend toward the authority of right would be for him to hold a }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid14112858 projectivism about the right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 . What we project, when we make judgments about blameworthiness and the right are not our desires, but reac tive attitudes through which we make and hold one another to (legitimate) demands. Of course, Hobbes might do better by both the good and the right were he to accept some kind of norm expressivism like Gibbardquote  s, which holds that these respective normative judgments express our acceptance of norms that }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid6767882 warrant}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   their respective attitudes, but that is another matter (Gibbard 1990). \par In }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 The Elements of Law}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , Hobbes contrasts human beings with other 舠'd2living creatures舡'd3 who 舠'd2}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734\charrsid2492009 have n}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 o conception of right and wrong舡'd3 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 EL}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : I.19.\u182'a6 5). Such creatures, Hobbes says, experience 舠'd2pleasure and pain舡'd3 and so have desires and aversions.}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar \s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1 \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0  23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \cs17 34 s20\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 In }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 Leviathan}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34 s20\insrsid2430041\charrsid8534809 , Hobbes calls pleasure and pain the \uc1舠'd2appearance[s]舡'd3 of delight and aversion, respectively (1994: 6.\u167'a410).}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   What they lack is any attitude of 舠'd2censure of one another舡'd3 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 EL}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 :I.19.\u182'a6 5). If Hobbes were to accept a projectivist metaethics of right according  to which judgments of right and their conceptual correlates express reactive attitudes like indignation, blame, and censure, he could then explain why in lacking th