41 ing}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 reasons of self-interest for doing so (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 DC}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 : 2.\u167'a410; }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : 13.\u182'a613, 26.}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 passim}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 ). Sovereigns are established, as it were, }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid2430041 either }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 from below, by subjects covenanting with one anothe r to authorize and follow a sovereign (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : 17), or from above, by conquest. An obligation to follow the sovereignquote  s commands follows directly from the covenant authorizing him. But even in }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid7626587 conquest}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 , Hobbes is clear that 舠'd2it is not . . . victory tha t giveth the right of dominion, but his own covenant,舡'd3 which the vanquished enter into when they submit to the conqueror and promise to obey as the price of survival (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : 20.\u167'a411). Hobbes distinguishes between the condition of a slave who is kept in thrall by chains and threats of reprisals, on the one hand, and a 舠'd2servant舡'd3 who 舠'd2 upon promise not to run away, nor to do violence to his master, is trusted by him舡'd3 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : 20.\u167'a4 10), on the other. And he explicitly analogizes the case of servants to that of submitting subjects.  \par }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 If masters and sovereigns }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 thus}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918   trust their servants and subjects, respectively, they must think that believing oneself to be obligated can make a difference in conduct that cannot fully be explained by motives of self-interest. }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 And t} {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 his is far from the }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 only place in which}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 Hobbes relies on this difference}{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 between motivation by self-interest and motivation by a sense of right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918  . The most central, of course, is in the making of the covenant itself. Since a covenant involves a transfer of rights by its very nature, }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid7626587 it is }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 only possible if the }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 covenanting }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918  parties see themselves as giving themselves and one another a reason to comply that is not reducible to self-interest. Or to put the point the other way around, individuals who recognize and know t hemselves to recognize only reasons of self-interest cannot covenant. But there are many other places also where Hobbes recognizes the possibility of conscientious conduct. Some particularly important examples for his political philosophy are instances  in which sovereignsquote commands conflict with subjectsquote consciences}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 or, contrariwise, when a proposed act of sedition would violate conscience. Thus, Hobbes says that}{tlch cs1 \af0  \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 舠'd2subjects will hardly be drawn into the field and fight with courage against their consciences}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 舡'd3 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 Behemoth}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 .}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 185). And that 舠'd2}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918  though a man be discontent, yet if in his own opinion there be no just cause of stirring against, or resisting the government established, nor any pretence to justify his resistance, and to procure aid, he}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   will never show it}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid4463918 舡'd3}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 EL}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  : 2.8). \par However, this still leaves a large question hanging. If it takes the sovereignquote s command to make genuine law, including of the laws of nature, how then can Hobbes accept the authority of right? But Hobbes cannot possibly think, and does not  think, that it takes the sovereignquote s command to }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 obligate}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  , since the sovereign can himself exist, only if a covenant that establishes him and authority obligates independently of his command. Moreover, there are reasons of }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 right}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 why, at least in Hobbesquote s view, it takes the sovereignquote s command to create genuine law. These reasons fit, briefly, under two main headings: publicity and assurance.  \par Genuine law requires genuine publicity\emdash public practices and institutions\emdash and those are unavailable in the state o f nature by definition. Second, like any covenant, the covenant establishing the sovereign requires joint performance and is void under reasonable suspicion of nonperformance. Covenanters will need assurance, therefore, not just that there will be reaso ns of right to comply, but that less conscientious individuals will have reasons to comply beyond their being obligated to. The crucial point is not that the covenanters might have a strategic, self-interested reason for this assurance; }{tlch cs1  \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid7626587 they have reasons for assurance that are grounded in the authority of right itself}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  . Perfectly conscientious beings who know one another to be so might not need the assurance provided by the sovereignquote s sanctions, but ordinary human beings, knowing one another to be guided b oth by conscience and by self-interest, do. Since reasonable suspicion of nonperformance voids contract, even conscientious subjects have reasons of right for wanting there to be reasons of self-interest for compliance also. But this does not mean that  the reasons of right derive their authority from self-interest}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid1584721 }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 in any way. It just means that they would not bind to performance }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 in foro externo }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 unless sanction-creating reasons of self-interest were in play also. \par }\pard \ltrpar\qc \li0i0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid354734 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734 V. PROJECTIVISM ABOUT THE RIGHT \par }\pard \ltrpar\ql  i720\li0i0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid354734 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 In this l ast section, I want to close with some remarks about how Hobbes might accommodate the elements of his thought that tend in the direction of the authority of right by holding a projectivism about the right that is analogous to his projectivism about the go od. The idea, in a nutshell, is that there is no less philosophical motivation for holding that judgments of praiseworthiness, moral obligation, and moral right express or 舠'd2project舡'd3  reactive attitudes through which we hold one another responsible than ther e is for thinking that judgments of good and evil express or project desires and aversions. We have seen that Hobbes regards the concepts of moral right and wrong as intrinsically related to moral responsibility, blame, and excuse. And Strawsonian react ive attitudes find their way into his moral psychology}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid10620481 also}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 . For example, Hobbes says that 舠'd2}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0   34\insrsid354734\charrsid3825592 indignation}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 舡'd3 is 舠'd2a}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid14877376  nger for great hurt done to another, when we conceive the same to be done injury}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 舡'd3 (}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734 L}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 : 6.\u167 'a421). Of course, if Hobbes were to think that indignation is a reaction to a prior }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid13729722 belief}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   about injury and wrong, he could not then say that these beliefs about right project the reactive attitude. But there is no philosophical reason for Hobbes to be a 舠'd2judgmentalist舡'd3 about reactive attitudes that would not ap ply also to being a judgmentalist about desire.}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid354734 \chftn { ootnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0 tlch cs1  \af0\afs24\alang1033 \ltrch cs0  23 s24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0 \cs17 34\super\insrsid2430041\charrsid13114856 \chftn }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid2430041\charrsid13114856 }{ tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34 s20\insrsid2430041 For arguments against \uc1舠'd2judgmentalist舡'd3 theories of emotion, see Dquote Arms and Jacobson 2000 and Nye 2009.}}}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   Neither view, moreover, seems to fit with Hobbesquote s fundamental philosophical orientations. \par How, then, would a projectivism about the right fit with a projectivism about the good? Hobbes believes that deliberation is }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid10620481 but}{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734   the succession of appetites and aversions and that the will is simply the last appetite before action. There is no doubt that such a stripped-down view of deliberation and the will fits less comfortably with a doctrine of the authority o f right than a moral psychology and philosophy of action that connects these more tightly to autonomous agency. Only the latter, it would seem, can best fit with a moral and political philosophy that give authority and consent fundamental roles. \par Nonethele ss, there is nothing that is flatly inconsistent between Hobbesian deliberation and the authority of right. Just as a Kantian ethics and moral psychology can be fit within a sufficiently formal Humean theory of motivation (for example, by making Rawls quote s distinction between object-dependent and principle-dependent desires), so also might a projectivism about the right be fit with a Hobbesian projectivism about the good (Rawls 2000). Thus we might regard one of the 舠'd2subjects舡'd3  Hobbes discusses in the passage quoted above who forbears self-interested rebellion because he lacks 舠'd2just cause,舡'd3  as having his desires affected by his reactive attitudes in ways that make his judgments of good influenced by his judgments of right. Realizing that such rebellion would  be blameworthy by imaginatively placing himself in an impartial position and blaming rebellion from that perspective, he desires not to rebel, which he expresses with the judgment that that would be bad to do (and good to forbear doing) because it would b e wrong.  \par I should reiterate, in conclusion, that I have not been trying to convince you that Hobbes actually accepted the authority of right. My point has rather been to show that there are elements of his thought that definitely point in that direction  and that other elements that are widely thought to rule it out, definitely do not. Once we have cleared the latter away, Hobbes could accept the doctrine without compromising anything fundamental to his view. \par }\pard \ltrpar\ql  i720\li0i0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid354734 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab Stephen Darwall \par 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab 	ab Yale University \par \column }{tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid14877376  \par }\pard \ltrpar\ql  i720\li0i0\sa240\widctlpar	x7280\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid354734 {tlch cs1 \af0 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 	ab  \par }\pard \ltrpar\ql  i-720\li720i0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum aauto\adjustrightin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid354734 {tlch cs1 \af34 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid2429256 Anscombe, G. E. M. (1958). 舠'd2 Modern Moral Philosophy,舡'd3 }{tlch cs1 \ai\af34 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid2429256 Philosophy}{tlch cs1 \af34 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid2429256 , 33: 1-19.}{tlch cs1 \af34 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734  \par }{tlch cs1 \af34 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid10510487 Aristotle (1980). }{tlch cs1 \ai\af34 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid10510487 The Nicomachean Ethics}{tlch cs1 \af34 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734\charrsid10510487  , ed. David Ross. New York: Oxford University Press}{tlch cs1 \af34 \ltrch cs0  34\insrsid354734 . References to chapter and section number. \par Barbeyrac, Jean (1749). }{tlch cs1 \af34 \ltrch cs0 \i 34\insrsid354734\charrsid7999758 Historical and Critical Account of the 